There are two correctness issues:

1. You need to declare and initialize `result`.

2. `result = result + &#39;0&#39;` appends to the wrong side of the string, reversing the output. Use `result = &#39;0&#39; + result` or reverse the result manually before returning. Appending to a string repeatedly in a loop can suffer from [Shlemiel the painter’s algorithm](https://www.joelonsoftware.com/2001/12/11/back-to-basics/).


Here&#39;s a simple re-write:

    def binary_converter(i):
        result = &quot;&quot;
    
        while i: 
            result = str(i % 2) + result
            i //= 2
    
        return result if result else &quot;0&quot;

Here&#39;s a re-write using lists:

    def binary_converter(i):
        result = []
    
        while i: 
            result.append(i % 2)
            i &gt;&gt;= 1
    
        return &quot;&quot;.join(map(str, result)) if result else &quot;0&quot;

Or use the builtin function [`bin`](https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#bin). Use `bin(42)[2:]` if you need to chop off the `0b` prefix.

Note that none of these functions take negative numbers into consideration.

I know this isn&#39;t technically answering your question, but just in case you didn&#39;t know, Python has built-in functionality for converting numbers to binary string representations.

With [bin](https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#bin):

    bin(3)  # &quot;0b11&quot;

With [format](https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html#format):

    format(3, &quot;b&quot;)  # &quot;11&quot;

