Most likely, the problem is with the loop for breaking the input line into token. The &#39;strtok&#39; is called twice on the input data, with only one NULL check.

If the second strtok call return NULL, the code will fail (crash) on the strcmp. Consider revising the loop body to:

~~~
  while (fgets(buffer, 30, stdin)) {
    buffer[strlen(buffer)-1]=&#39;\0&#39;;
    if ( strcmp(buffer, &quot;.&quot;) == 0 ) break ;
    char* token = strtok(buffer, &quot; \n&quot;);
    while (token != NULL){
      int i = 0;
      while (i &lt; entry_count+1) {
        if (!strcmp(entries[i].word, token))
          entries[i].counter++;
        i++;
      }
      line_count++;
      // Place strtok here
      token = strtok(NULL, &quot; \n&quot;);   }
    }
~~~
also note that the posted code will fix the problem that cause the first token on every line to be ignored.

Your function processes the tokens out of order. You skip the first `token` entirely overwriting the pointer `token` before it is used with:

    char* token = strtok(buffer, &quot; \n&quot;);
    while (token != NULL){
      token = strtok(NULL, &quot; \n&quot;); 

Next the following line is superfluous given your delimiter of `&quot; \n&quot;`. The `&#39;\n&#39;` you attempt to overwrite with the following code with never be part of `token`:

    buffer[strlen(buffer)-1]=&#39;\0&#39;;

You are using `&#39;.&#39;` to mark the end-of-input so you do not need to process the final line. You avoid this problem you break your nested loop with a simple `goto` statement,  e.g.:

        while (fgets (buffer, MAXC, stdin)) {
            ...
            while (token != NULL) {
                if (!strcmp (token, &quot;.&quot;))               /* compare != &#39;.&#39; */
                    goto done;
                ...
        }
        done:;
        
        return line_count;
    }

Assuming `entry_count` is the number of elements in `entries`, then your `+1` causes you to read beyond the bounds of `entries` likely resulting in a SegFault. While it is impossible to verify give the complete code that is missing from your question, it looks like you intended:

            while (i &lt; entry_count) {               /* +1 causeses UB */

Your call to `token = strtok(NULL, &quot; \n&quot;);` to get the next token should be the last statement in your loop, not the first, otherwise you have skipped a token.

Putting it altogether, it looks like you would need something similar to:

    #define MAXC 128    /* max number of characters per word/line */
    ...
    int process_stream (WordCountEntry entries[], int entry_count)
    {
        short line_count = 0;
        char buffer[MAXC];
        const char *delim = &quot; \n&quot;;                      /* set delim once */
    
        while (fgets (buffer, MAXC, stdin)) {
            char *token = strtok(buffer, delim);
            while (token != NULL) {
                if (!strcmp (token, &quot;.&quot;))               /* compare != &#39;.&#39; */
                    goto done;
                int i = 0;
                while (i &lt; entry_count) {               /* +1 causeses UB */
                    if (!strcmp(entries[i].word, token))
                        entries[i].counter++;
                    i++;
                }
                line_count++;
                token = strtok(NULL, delim);            /* now get next token */
            }
        }
        done:;
        
        return line_count;
    }

**Short Example**

Per your comments you wanted to be able to handle single-words or multiple-words per-line. The function above does that, but you may have other problems in code you haven&#39;t posted. To validate the function above, a short implementation was written. So long as your code provides similar input, the function above will satisfy your needs. The short example used was:

    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
    #include &lt;string.h&gt;
    
    #define NENT  16    /* max number of entries (no. elements in array) */
    #define MAXC 128    /* max number of characters per word / line */
    
    typedef struct {
        char word[MAXC];
        int counter;
    } WordCountEntry;
    
    int process_stream (WordCountEntry entries[], int entry_count)
    {
        short line_count = 0;
        char buffer[MAXC];
        const char *delim = &quot; \n&quot;;                      /* set delim once */
    
        while (fgets (buffer, MAXC, stdin)) {
            char *token = strtok(buffer, delim);
            while (token != NULL) {
                if (!strcmp (token, &quot;.&quot;))               /* compare != &#39;.&#39; */
                    goto done;
                int i = 0;
                while (i &lt; entry_count) {               /* +1 causeses UB */
                    if (!strcmp(entries[i].word, token))
                        entries[i].counter++;
                    i++;
                }
                line_count++;
                token = strtok(NULL, delim);            /* now get next token */
            }
        }
        done:;
        
        return line_count;
    }
    
    int main (int argc, char **argv) {
        
        WordCountEntry wce[NENT] = { { .word = &quot;&quot; } };
        int n = 0;
        
        if (argc &lt; 2) {
            fputs (&quot;error: insufficient arguments.\n&quot;, stderr);
            return 1;
        }
        
        for (int i = 1; i &lt; (argc &lt; NENT ? argc : NENT); i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j &lt; i; j++) {
                if (!strcmp (wce[j].word, argv[i]))
                    goto next;
            }
            strcpy (wce[i-1].word, argv[i]);
            n++;
            next:;
        }
        
        puts (&quot;Looking for words:&quot;);
        
        if (!process_stream (wce, n))
            fputs (&quot;(user canceled input)\n&quot;, stderr);
        
        puts (&quot;\nResult:&quot;);
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++)
            printf (&quot;%s: %d\n&quot;, wce[i].word, wce[i].counter);
    }

**Example Use/Output**

    $ ./bin/wordcountentry cat nap dog
    Looking for words:
    cat
    cat
    nap
    .
    
    Result:
    cat: 2
    nap: 1
    dog: 0

or with multiple-words per-line:

    $ ./bin/wordcountentry cat nap dog
    Looking for words:
    cat dog dog
    cat dog
    nap .
    
    Result:
    cat: 2
    nap: 1
    dog: 3

There may be other problems in your code and it is impossible to be sure this will correct all issues due to the lack of [A Minimal, Complete, and Verifiable Example (MCVE)](http://stackoverflow.com/help/mcve), but given what you had, this should address the problems that are identifiable, though there may be others. 

